{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628926"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17249"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17249"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.03,0.44,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69586"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9939"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55038"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7160"},{"type":"tags","id":"8412"},{"type":"tags","id":"8467"},{"type":"tags","id":"10000"},{"type":"tags","id":"10001"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23312"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69586"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe oesophagus uses coordinated muscle contractions to propel food from the pharynx to the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes primary peristalsis in the oesophagus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initiated by voluntary swallowing and controlled by the medulla","Initiated by gastric distension","Triggered automatically by local stretch receptors","Controlled by vagal reflexes only","Triggered by oesophageal inflammation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary peristalsis is initiated by voluntary swallowing and controlled by the medulla oblongata\u003C/strong\u003E. This coordinated wave of muscle contraction begins in the pharynx and progresses down the oesophagus, propelling the food bolus towards the stomach. The sequence is controlled by the swallowing centre in the medulla, which coordinates the timing and strength of muscle contractions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriggered automatically by local stretch receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes secondary peristalsis, which occurs in response to distension or residual food in the oesophagus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControlled by vagal reflexes only\u003C/strong\u003E - While vagal input is important, primary peristalsis requires integrated control from the medulla\u0027s swallowing centre\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiated by gastric distension\u003C/strong\u003E - Gastric distension does not trigger oesophageal peristalsis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriggered by oesophageal inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - Inflammation may alter motility but does not trigger normal peristaltic waves\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrimary peristalsis involves sequential contraction of circular smooth muscle above the food bolus and relaxation below it, ensuring efficient transport of food to the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary peristalsis in the oesophagus is initiated by voluntary swallowing and controlled by the medulla oblongata.","Secondary peristalsis is triggered by local stretch receptors in response to distension or residual food.","Both primary and secondary peristalsis involve sequential contraction of circular smooth muscle above the food bolus and relaxation below it."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55038"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17249"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55038"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T11:09:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T11:09:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9939"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69586"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdA